Reflection on the very American ideal of labour rights as human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have tabled a bill to establish the organization of trade unions as a civil right.
“Just as unions die, so do middle-class jobs,” said Ellison, a Minnesota Democrat and deputy chairman of the Progressive Caucus in Congress.
That’s why I’m proud to present the Employee Empowerment Act together with the civil rights icon John Lewis.
This groundbreaking law gives workers the same legal opportunities to discriminate on the basis of the organization of trade unions as on other forms of discrimination – stopping anti-unionist forces.
Supplementing the national labour law to provide a way for workers exposed to discrimination to organize a union representation, to sue in a civil court for justice – and to obtain damages or penalties – is a sensible and necessary initiative.
But it is certainly not a radical initiative – at least not by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis and the other sponsors of their bill suggest is to link back to a very American idea.
Despite the setbacks unions have faced in recent years — in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country — Americans have once encouraged countries around the world to recognize, expand, and uphold labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country called democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to unite in one breath.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his staff encouraged the country to pass a constitution designed to ensure that the militarized autocracy of Hedki Tojos would be replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that the workers and their unions played a role in creating a new Japan, they used a language that explicitly recognized that “workers’ rights to unification and joint negotiation and action are guaranteed.”
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his staff urged the Germans to write a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler’s fascism would be replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing the fact that the workers would have to organize themselves and raise their voices in the new nation, the Germans inserted a clause that explicitly stated: "The right to establish associations in order to secure and improve the working and economic conditions is guaranteed to every individual and every profession or trade.
Agreements that limit or aim to diminish this right are null and void; measures aimed at it are unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights, which designed the Universal Declaration of Human Rights as adopted by the United Nations as a worldwide agreement in 1948, Roosevelt and the other writers made a guarantee that “everyone has the right to form or join trade unions to protect their interests.”
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
As this country discussed with other countries how to form civil and democratic societies, Americans declared that the right to form a trade union – and then that this trade union should participate in collective bargaining as an equal partner with companies and government agencies – must be protected.
After these rights have come under fire in America, it is indeed very wise to reconsider the American ideal, according to which the working population must have the right to unite and to make themselves heard in a free and open society.
As Pastor Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the workers’ movement did not limit the strength of the nation, but increased it.
By raising the standard of living of millions of people, work miraculously created a market for industry and lifted the entire nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack the work forget these simple truths, but history preserves them.
History remembers, and so should we.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of civil rights as a protection against discrimination in the creation of workers' representations - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis renew the ideals that have made America great in the past and fulfilled the promise of democracy.
Judge Temporarily Stops Law That All Abortion Clinics in Louisiana Could Force Closure
A U.S. federal judge on Sunday provisionally halted the implementation of a law in Louisiana, which lawyers say likely led to the closure of all five abortion clinics in the state.
This measure, which was enacted by Bobby Jindal, Governor of Louisiana, in June and is due to come into force on Sept. 1, would force doctors performing abortions to have a right to receive patients at a hospital within a 30-mile radius to acquire their practice.
However, the judge’s decision means that doctors can continue to perform abortions legally for the time being, while applying for such a right.
"The plaintiffs can continue to work in accordance with the law while they are working to obtain these rights," Federal Judge John deGravelles wrote in his ruling.
Within a month, a hearing is scheduled for the judge to bring about a more lasting decision for the law.
Abortion advocates welcomed the decision, the latest in a series of rulings against similar measures, saying that doctors are thus giving more time to gain hospital admission rights.
“Today’s decision means that Louisiana women are avoiding a deceptive law that wants to take away their health and rights,” said Nancy Northup, president and chair of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which had sued on behalf of three of the state’s five clinics to stop the law.
It was not immediately clear whether the judgment also extended to doctors from the two clinics who did not join the lawsuit and had also applied for induction rights.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have enacted similar laws, with courts in Alabama and Mississippi recently declaring such measures unconstitutionally.
Key parts of a Texas law that would have forced most of the state’s remaining clinics to close were halted by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion advocates and the American College of Ostretricians and Gynecologists as well as the American Medical Association agree that instructional rights require unnecessary restrictions from doctors.
Abortion opponents oppose the fact that the measures serve to protect women’s health, although some also welcomed the effects of a closure of clinics.
Only one doctor performing abortions in Louisiana has patient information rights, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all other doctors in the state are forced to stop performing abortions, this doctor would no longer perform the surgery out of fear for his safety, the group said.
In their argument against the verdict, Louisiana state officials said they would not punish doctors for performing abortions while their requests for patient detention rights were still pending.
