Production in the Eurozone at a 13-month low
The increase in production in the eurozone slowed in August to the lowest point in the last 13 months, according to a closely monitored study.
The final Markit Purchasing Manager Index of the Manufacturing Industry (PMI) fell to 50.7 in August, after a 51.8 in July.
A statement above 50 indicates an expansion.
New orders declined, and factories experienced break-ins at a time of rising tensions between the EU and Russia over Ukraine.
The figures arrive ahead of the European Central Bank (ECB) meeting on Thursday.
Markets expect the bank to have a clear plan to deal with a hesitant recovery in the eurozone and the imminent deflation at an inflation rate of just 0.3%.
There is speculation that the head of the ECB, Mario Draghi, could provide further information over the course of this week on whether he is considering a quantitative relief for the eurozone, in line with those made by the UK and the US during the financial crisis.
“Although small growth is better than no growth at all, the slowing effects of increasing economic and geopolitical uncertainties have become clearer for manufacturers,” said Rob Dobson, senior economist at Markit.
The factory PMI for Germany, Russia’s largest trading partner in the EU, fell to its lowest level in 11 months at 51.4.
Meanwhile, the PMI fell to 46.9 in the bloc’s second-largest economic nation, France.
France remains a child of concern, as does the descent of Italy from a solid expansion to stagnation.
Indications that growth incentives are no longer taking hold in the key industrial mechanism in Germany, Spain and the Netherlands are also not reassuring,” said Mr. Dobson.
The decline of the industry is probably fueling the fire of analysts who expect further monetary or fiscal incentives.
A positive news came from the Republic of Ireland, where the PMI rose to 57.3, the highest level since the end of 1999.
Howard Archer, chief economics expert at IHS Global Insight, said: “The best thing you can say for the August purchasing manager index of the eurozone manufacturing industry is that after that the sector continues to grow.”
He added: “Producers in the eurozone are obviously finding life quite difficult at the moment, as current heightened geopolitical tensions – especially with regard to Russia and Ukraine – increase uncertainties in the continuing difficult conditions in many countries.
These increased uncertainties have clearly affected the economy - in particular, and consumer confidence, and are likely to cause some orders to be delayed or even cancelled, especially large orders.
