4 Tips for Better Underwater Photos and Videos
If you want to take photos or videos underwater, there is a choice of devices.
The most affordable option is a waterproof point-and-shoot, like the Nikon Coolpix AW120 or an action cam like the GoPro Hero3+ Silver Edition, both of which are to have for about $300.
I took these photos at a family party with multiple cameras, all of which are available at a price under $350.
Regardless of the equipment, there are a few rules for the best results.
Check your equipment twice.
Even if you have a waterproof camera, make sure that the battery compartment and other compartments are tightly sealed.
Also set your camera to the photos or videos you want to take.
Some cameras and camcorders have scene and recording modes that optimize exposure time for the insulated underwater conditions.
And before you jump in, check to what depth your equipment is working.
Some cameras are only allowed for up to 5 feet, others up to 50 or 60 feet.
Search our shopping guide and reviews for digital cameras for conventional and waterproof models.
Make multiple shots - because many won't work.
Point-and-shoot cameras have an LCD that allows you to compose images, action cams usually don’t.
Even if you have an LCD, it is difficult to look at this underwater, and the right image setting is a matter of luck.
So take a lot of shots.
If your camera has a row mode that takes a series of shots with slightly altered exposure settings, use it.
Stay close to the surface.
The light gets dramatically worse the further you move away from the surface.
So, if possible, stay close to the surface when shooting in a pool, lake or sea.
This also allows you to add more color to your photos; the deeper you go, the less color you will see.
Closely approach the objects.
This is also good advice on land, but it is all the more important underwater because of the poor light conditions.
It’s especially important when you’re working with an action cam: These devices often have a fixed wide-angle lens, which means you need to get closer to your objects if they’re to fill the entire frame.
