The virus has also spread to Guinea, Sierra Leone and Nigeria.
In total, more than 1500 people have already died and thousands more have been imprisoned.
Foreign companies withdraw employees
Everywhere in resource-rich countries, companies are suspending their operations.
Foreign companies such as the steel company Arcelor Mittal are withdrawing their employees, several international airlines no longer fly to the affected regions.
The local traders and farmers also react: only a few merchants still leave their hometowns to procure supplies.
In some areas of Sierra Leone and Liberia, which are quarantined, cocoa and coffee beans important for export are rotting in the fields, among others.
Farmers do not dare to leave their homes for the harvest.
Food is scarce
“People will travel less and less,” says Phillipe De Vreyer, a Paris-based expert on the West African economy.
For example, the man who usually goes to the market and sells his vegetables prefers to stay at home.
The population is therefore feeling the consequences of the epidemic directly and urgently: food is becoming scarce.
In the markets, the stock of basic foodstuffs such as rice is dwindling.
At the same time, the region, which is heavily dependent on international companies, is in danger of image damage - with far-reaching consequences.
The biggest danger is that international companies will basically avoid the area for a long time, says Philippe Hugon of the French think tank Iris.
It is important to know how far and how long the virus will spread.
“Investors may have the impression that it is dangerous to live in Guinea, Sierra Leone and Liberia and thus also to invest,” Hugon warns.
The disease also affects the stressed state budgets of the states
The disease also affects the already strained state budgets of the affected states.
The rating agency Moody's fears that its budgets will be heavily strained by the high expenditures on the health system and in addition by the deteriorating economy.
The African Development Bank has already promised to provide $60 million (€45 million) to the health systems of the affected countries.
