Genetic Disorder Often Misdiagnosed
One Briton says she thought as a result of a misdiagnosis over many years that she would die.
Karin Rodgers lived almost her entire youth in the belief that she had only a few years to live after being diagnosed with another disease.
She actually suffered from Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease (CMT) — a group of inherited disorders that damage the nerves outside the brain and spinal cord.
Charity CMT UK reported that misdiagnosis is a common problem in people with CMT because so little is known about this disease.
About 23,000 people in the UK are believed to suffer from CMT, which can lead to motor disorders such as muscle weakness, an unsafe gait and curved toes.
Patients also suffer from numbness or pain. The disease is incurable and progressive, which means that the symptoms get worse over time.
When Rodgers was 13, she believed she suffered from Friedreich ataxia (FA) – a disease with very poor chances of survival.
Rodgers thought she would sit in a wheelchair before she was 18, and die before her 30th birthday.
The mother of two, who is now 51 years old, said: “As a child, I knew I couldn’t do the same thing as the others.
I fell down all the time and everything took longer with me.
I was never able to ride roller skates or skateboards with the other kids and was often teased at school because of my way of walking and running.
Rodgers said that at the age of 13, after several surgeries to relieve her Achilles tendons and stretch her feet, she saw her medical records when her doctor had left the room and read that she had AF.
“I felt guilty because I had been curious, so I didn’t tell anyone, but I went home, searched for the disease in the library, and wrote to the FA Society,” she said.
When I got an answer, I was shocked and terribly panicked.
I thought I would be in a wheelchair at 18 and die at 25, and in between I would slowly lose all my skills.
I did it all by myself and planned my own funeral.
She said when she turned 17, she realized that her abilities had not diminished as much as she had imagined and interviewed her doctor.
He just got up and hugged me and said, "My love, I don't think you have that, otherwise you'd be in a wheelchair by now."
I think you have something far less life-threatening.
After some genetic tests, her CMT was found.
“When he explained to me what CMT was, I felt like I was a winner,” she said.
Charity CMT UK has launched a CMT Awareness Month to raise awareness of this disease.
