Tax burden on business people in the Washington area rises with economic recovery
A recovery in the economy means more customers, more sales and new jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
State and local tax rulings for businesses in the country rose slightly last year, as economic recovery accelerated, according to a newly released study last week, and Washington-area companies were no exception.
Companies in the District, Maryland and Virginia jointly paid $27.6 billion to government and local authorities in fiscal 2013, an increase of 3.8 percent from 2012 revenues of $26.6 billion.
The state and local tax burden on companies rose 4.3 percent to $671 billion last year, up from 3.9 percent the year before, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after several years of declining measures in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes rose more than local taxes, by 4.3 percent, according to the study conducted by service agency Ernst & Young with the Center for State Taxation, a tax policy group.
More than half of the District’s tax revenue, 56 percent, comes from corporate taxes, while 36 percent of Maryland’s revenue comes from businesses.
Virginia has the lowest corporate tax revenue at 28 percent.
Much of the increase in tax revenues is due to a recovery in real estate values of companies, the researchers say, which led to a 3.7 percent increase in real estate taxes this year after the three consecutive years with growth rates of less than 1 percent.
While a large portion of these profits came from large states such as California, New York and Texas, the process seems to apply to the Washington area as well.
Companies in the District, Maryland and Virginia jointly paid more than $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, up from $9.6 billion in 2012 – an increase of 4.2 percent over the course of a year.
But the apparent recovery in property values in Maryland is not as effective in increasing state and local tax revenues, as property taxes here amount to just over one-fifth of corporate tax rulings.
Companies in Virginia and D.C. pay nearly half of their state and local taxes in the form of real estate taxes.
“In Maryland, a large portion of the property, especially in the D.C. tax area, is either owned by the government or by non-profit organizations that do not pay property taxes,” said Douglas Lindholm, managing director of the Center on State Taxation.
Maryland is therefore forced to rely much more on income taxes, for example, to be able to provide the same services that other states offer.
The recent recovery in corporate tax revenues cannot be attributed to the recovery of the real estate market alone
Corporate revenues also appear to be recovering, according to the data.
Companies in the region reported income taxes on state-owned organizations of $2.3 billion compared to $2.1 billion in 2012.
Maryland took in $1 billion in corporate income taxes, the highest amount in the region.
