We showed a powerful tribe at our riddle run of the summer series "Mein Stück vom Rhöner Glück" last Friday.
Several of these tree giants are still in the county, the specimen shown is the "Geißruheiche" above Unterweißenbrunn.
A bumpy footpath leads up to the 600-year-old oak.
It goes past domes, basalt stone heaps and basalt stone seas.
A little below the quarry from Bauersberg, a kilometer north of the road to Weisbach, there it stands.
Vital looks like the natural monument, it protrudes beyond the other trees in the area and is reminiscent of an American mammoth tree with a circumference of more than eight meters.
A small Buddha on a stump indicates that it is a spiritual or mystical place.
However, despite extensive research, there was only evidence of the origin of the name.
Dr. Wolfgang Schneider has consulted the Bischofsheimer Archiv and interviewed older people from Unterweißenbrunn to find out what it has to do with the Geißruheiche.
The result of his investigations remained the fairly sober explanation for the name.
Until about 80 years ago, the goat herders were supposed to have driven their animals from sub-white fountains onto the fields that had been toiled and freed from stones.
At the foot of the tree, the animal shepherds who were exhausted from the ascent are said to have rested.
In the meantime, the area has regained its importance, because in the meadows, goat herds actually graze again.
The area has also been declared the core zone of the biosphere reserve, Schneider further found out.
However, when entering the stone collections, caution should be exercised, because the basalt warmed up by the sun is also a popular place for crucifixion.
A hiking trail leads from Unterweißenbrunn to the tree, which is somewhat hidden.
Other paths are signposted, climbing in the direction of Hochrhön and inviting for an extended hike.
Where is the Water Castle?
However, a water castle, which is sought in our next task, is rather rare to find in the height.
The reflection in the ditch already gives a good impression of the building, but we have in the district some historical buildings to which the building counterfeit could fit.
Where is our "piece of Rhöner Glück"?
