After weeks of tug-of-war, Italy’s Prime Minister and current EU President, Matteo Renzi, has pushed through the nomination of his Foreign Minister Federica Mogherini as head of EU foreign policy against strong conservative resistance at last week’s EU Special Summit.
Renzi considers, as the pro-government daily La Repubblica puts it, the appeal of his Mogherini, also a favourite in the government team, to strengthen the position of the Social Democrats and his own in the EU.
He also expects a boost for his "reform package" in Italy.
Last but not least, Renzi hopes to calm the ever-contesting left-wing party base against him, because Mogherini is assigned to this - albeit rather in a moderate way.
Compared to the conservative representatives with Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker and the Poland nominated as President of the Council Donald Tusk, according to the prevailing opinion in Rome, a political balance will be established.
At the same time, the EU’s chief diplomat will be the deputy of Commission President Juncker.
The pending approval of the European Parliament is considered safe.
Otherwise, President Giorgio Napolitano would hardly have called the nomination of the 41-year-old politician of the ruling Democratic Party (PD) an "important recognition" of Italy's role in the EU.
La Repubblica is optimistic that the Mogherini, who has been in leading party offices for almost two decades and is known for her ambition, will be able to meet the “enormous challenges”.
The native Roman is married and has two daughters.
Her party career began in 1996 as a political scientist with a doctorate in the youth organization of the then Democratici di Sinistra (Left Democrats), which joined forces with the Catholic Centre Party Margherita in 2008 to form today’s social democratic PD.
In 1999, Mogherini became Vice President of the European Community Organisation of Socialist Youth for three years.
With the 2001 election to the Party Council of the Left Democrats, she entered the high party policy, working in the foreign policy department, whose head she soon became.
It occupied traditional focal points of Italian foreign policy such as the Middle East, became known through studies on the NATO deployment in Afghanistan, in which Italy is involved with a troop contingent, maintained contacts with the Social Democrats in Europe and with the Democrats in the United States.
Since 2008 she has been a member of the Chamber of Deputies, where she is an expert on defence and European and international affairs.
When Renzi became prime minister in February 2014, he appointed Mogherini as his foreign minister.
If the PD today again has a better relationship with the strong peace movement in the country, which contributed to the more than 40 percent votes of the party in the EU elections in May, then, as noted in PD circles, Federica Mogherini has a share of it.
The accusations in Brussels that the new EU foreign representative has too little diplomatic experience, i.e. lack of substance, are countered in the PD.
In Brussels, mainly by Poland and the Baltic members, the suspiciously realistic accents of Mogherini on the crisis in Ukraine are being persecuted and defamed as a "Russia-friendly course".
It supports the South Stream pipeline operated by the Russian company Gasprom, through which Russian natural gas is to be transported directly to southern Europe while bypassing Ukraine, which also serves the energy security of Italy.
After Renzi took office as EU president in July, Mogherini travelled to Moscow for her first state visit.
Photos they showed with Putin at the shake-hands were taken in Brussels with outrage, as well as inviting the Kremlin chief to an economic summit in Milan for October.
