Putin calls on Kiev to start ‘state talks’ with eastern Ukraine
According to Russian media reports, Russian President Vladimir Putin on Sunday demanded that the Ukrainian government stop fighting the separatists in the east of the country and immediately begin negotiations on the "statehood" of the apostate region.
His spokesman Dmitry Peskov later clarified that Putin did not mean that the territory of eastern Ukraine under the control of the separatists would become part of Russia, but that its status vis-<0xC3><0xA0>-vis Ukraine must be redefined in order to give the Russian-speaking region the power to represent its rights and interests.
Putin’s call to the Kiev government to negotiate on an equal footing with the pro-Russian insurgents, however, fits with the strategy he has apparently pursued since the beginning of the riots five months ago: help for the separatists in occupying territories and pressure on the Ukrainian government to enable the newly proclaimed region Novorossiya to effectively become independent for an alliance with Russia instead of the West.
In an interview with the state television channel Channel One, Putin condemned the Ukrainian military campaign to recapture the separatist-held territories in the eastern regions of Donetsk and Luhansk, which were seized in March and April after Moscow annexed the Ukrainian peninsula of Crimea on March 18.
The Kremlin and the Separatists have recently referred to the occupied territory as "Novorosia" or "Neurussia", a term reminiscent of the pre-revolutionary period of the Russian Empire.
Putin pointed out that all those who, in the course of Ukrainian politicians’ campaigns for the Oct. 26 elections and while government groups are attacking civilian communities in the areas held by separatists, hope for soon-to-be peace talks “caught in their illusions,” Itar-Tass reported.
"We need to immediately begin detailed discussions, not only on technical issues, but also on the political organization of society and the state status of Southeastern Ukraine, in order to safeguard the interests of the people living there," he said.
Peskov said Putin’s reference to statehood must be seen in the context of greater autonomy, which has been discussed for months by the Kiev leadership, in order to dispel fears in Russian-speaking areas that their cultural and linguistic rights are endangered.
Only the Ukrainian government can grant the necessary autonomy to the eastern regions, Peskov said.
This is not about negotiations between Ukraine and Russia, Peskov said, “because it is not about a conflict between Russia and Ukraine, but about an internal conflict in Ukraine.”
The Kremlin spokesman’s clarification on correcting the “misinterpretation” of Putin’s remarks underlined Russia’s claim to leadership in dealing with the separatist rebellion in the east, as opposed to the direct annexation of Crimea, where the majority of the 2 million inhabitants are ethnic Russians.
Moscow would have far greater difficulty annexing the Donetsk and Luhansk regions in eastern Ukraine, as most of the 6.5 million inhabitants are not Russians and polls from the pre-conflict period showed a broad majority for remaining in Ukraine.
The autonomy discussed by Russian diplomats at international forums would give regional governments in Ukraine the power to negotiate their own trade agreements and external relations, and thus give the Kremlin de facto control over an area that connects the Russian territory with Crimea.
The Black Sea peninsula, which was annexed five months ago, is the home port for most of the Russian navy, as well as an important trading port and historic coastal region.
The regions between the Rostov region in Russia and Crimea are also rich in mines, factories and foundries that produce important components for the Russian military.
In his June 7 inauguration speech, Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko proposed that Ukrainian legislation should consider additions to the constitution, after new elections, which would give the respective territories greater control over their finances and the status of languages.
But his idea of autonomy seems to be in sharp contrast to those of the Kremlin and the separatist rebels, whose armaments and incitement Moscow is accused of.
Putin’s last call to Kiev to negotiate with the separatist leaders on an equal footing followed another incursion by the rebels last week after Russian troops and tanks invaded eastern Ukraine over the previously peaceful region along the Azov Sea.
The Russian-backed separatists took control of Novoasovsk by hand, which Ukrainian security officials fear is the first step in a campaign to take over the strategic coastal region to Crimea.
For this reason, massive civilian and military preparations have begun to fortify Mariupol, a steel industry port with 500,000 inhabitants, located between Novoasovsk and the narrow access to the Crimean peninsula.
Poroshenko spoke at a meeting of EU leaders in Brussels on Saturday and urged action to prevent further Russian aggression against Ukraine, a former Soviet republic that has been independent for 23 years.
"We are near a point where there is no going back," Poroshenko warned.
Thousands of foreign troops and hundreds of foreign tanks are now on the territory of Ukraine.
The EU summit did not decide on concrete actions, the leadership called for the draft of further sanctions against Russia, which should come into force in the event of an unspecified escalation of the Ukraine crisis.
Ukrainian soldiers had to withdraw from their positions in Ilovajsk after two Russian tank columns and 1,000 soldiers invaded the Donetsk region last week to support the besieged separatists, said Colonel Andrij Lysenko, spokesman for the Ukrainian National Security and Defense Council reports on Saturday in Kiev.
The first likely 63 Ukrainian soldiers, who were imprisoned by the Russian invasion of Ilovajsk, were exchanged on Sunday for 10 Russian paratroopers who had been captured in Ukrainian territory a week ago, Lysenko said on Sunday.
